BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lawai-academic-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115115Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Law & AI Academic Fellowship
DESCRIPTION:The Institute for Law & AI (LawAI)\, an independent think tank 
 researching and advising on the legal challenges posed by artificial intel
 ligence\, is running its inaugural Law & AI Academic Fellowship for aspiri
 ng legal scholars who intend to go on the US legal academic job market. Th
 e fellowship is designed as an alternative to university-sponsored Visitin
 g Assistant Professor or law fellow positions: fellows spend the majority 
 of their time researching and writing articles for publication in law jour
 nals on the law of transformative AI\, and are prepared for the academic j
 ob market as part of a larger application package. Teaching is not require
 d\, which LawAI frames as a benefit over most university-affiliated positi
 ons\, though fellows who want teaching experience are encouraged to seek i
 t and LawAI and its affiliates may be able to help secure positions. Each 
 fellow is paired with an academic mentor from LawAI's network of affiliate
 d academics for ongoing support\, with more intensive help in the final st
 ages of the job application process including moot interviews and detailed
  feedback. Fellows may also inquire about spending time in residence at ac
 ademic institutions of interest. Candidates are selected in part on how we
 ll their research interests align with LawAI's: the institute expects AI t
 o reshape culture\, the economy\, public policy\, public administration\, 
 politics\, military affairs and geostrategy at least as profoundly as the 
 Industrial Revolution\, and asks whether a candidate's research is well-sc
 oped to changes of that magnitude. Areas of particular interest include ri
 sk regulation of transformative AI\, liability for AI harms\, AI and biose
 curity\, AI and cybersecurity\, executive branch use of transformative AI\
 , national security law\, law and AI infrastructure\, administrative law\,
  constitutional law\, international regulation\, AI in the judiciary\, and
  industrial policy. Full-time two-year role at USD 130\,000 per year\, bas
 ed in Washington DC\, Cambridge UK\, or remote. Applications close 31 July
  2026.\n\nOrganisation: Institute for Law & AI (LawAI)\nLocation: Washingt
 on DC\, USA\; Cambridge\, UK\; or remote\nAward: USD 130\,000 annual salar
 y. No application fee.\nDuration: Two years\, full-time\n\nMore: https://l
 aw-ai.org/career/academic-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdes
 k&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://law-ai.org/career/academic-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnou
 veaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, USA\; Cambridge\, UK\; or remote
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rand-cast-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115115Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260801
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260802
SUMMARY:Deadline: Center on AI\, Security\, and Technology (CAST) Fellowshi
 p
DESCRIPTION:RAND's Center on AI\, Security\, and Technology (CAST) runs a r
 olling fellowship for researchers working on AI security and technology po
 licy\, with mentorship from RAND policy experts. Fellows can be based in W
 ashington DC\, San Francisco or Pittsburgh\, work remotely within the Unit
 ed States\, or be based in the United Kingdom. Terms are flexible: engagem
 ents typically start at six months and can be extended up to three years\,
  full-time or part-time. US fellows receive an annual stipend ranging from
  USD 40\,000 to 200\,000 for full-time work depending on experience\, plus
  a monthly payment that can be put toward health and dental insurance\; UK
  fellows are compensated based on experience. The programme spans career s
 tages from undergraduate through mid-career. ELIGIBILITY: applicants must 
 be based in the US or UK\; US applicants need to be eligible for a governm
 ent security clearance\, and UK applicants must have a current and ongoing
  right to work in the UK. Current RAND staff are not eligible. ROLLING DEA
 DLINE: applications are submitted through an online form and reviewed quar
 terly\, with published cutoffs of 1 February\, 1 May\, 1 August and 1 Nove
 mber\, each answered by the first of the following month. The date recorde
 d here is the next cutoff (1 August 2026)\; the call does not close after 
 it. RAND notes that if one of its listed staff openings matches your inter
 est you should apply to that instead\, and suggests not applying to the fe
 llowship if you have submitted another CAST application within the last si
 x months.\n\nOrganisation: RAND Corporation\, Center on AI\, Security\, an
 d Technology (CAST)\nLocation: Washington DC\, San Francisco or Pittsburgh
 \, USA\, or remote within the United States\; fellows may also be based in
  the United Kingdom\nAward: US fellows: annual stipend from USD 40\,000 to
  200\,000 for full-time fellows depending on experience\, plus a monthly p
 ayment usable for health and dental insurance. UK fellows: compensation ba
 sed on experience. No application fee.\nDuration: Typically starts at 6 mo
 nths\, extendable up to 3 years\; full-time or part-time\n\nMore: https://
 www.rand.org/global-and-emerging-risks/centers/ai-security-and-technology/
 fellows.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.rand.org/global-and-emerging-risks/centers/ai-security-and-
 technology/fellows.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=r
 eferral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, San Francisco or Pittsburgh\, USA\, or remote with
 in the United States\; fellows may also be based in the United Kingdom
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai-alignment-foundation-aiaf-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260724T115115Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260817
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260818
SUMMARY:Deadline: AIAF Fellowship\, Autumn 2026
DESCRIPTION:An eight-week full-time empirical AI alignment research program
 me run by the AI Alignment Foundation\, with a dedicated research manager\
 , mentorship from senior researchers\, compute and infrastructure\, culmin
 ating in a Demo Day where fellows present their work. Fellows receive a US
 D 12\,000 stipend paid in two installments plus a compute budget. The prog
 ramme is fully remote for the research period\; Demo Day is hybrid in Los 
 Angeles and travel is covered for fellows who attend in person. ELIGIBILIT
 Y: open to all career stages\, including recent PhDs\, graduate students\,
  self-taught researchers and career-changers\, but candidates need a stron
 g machine learning background\, demonstrated engagement with alignment res
 earch\, prior independent research output\, and the ability to work autono
 mously. Non-US applicants are welcome provided they can make Pacific Time 
 meetings\; current graduate students may apply if they can confirm availab
 ility. This is explicitly a technical programme: the foundation says polic
 y-focused applicants should not apply. SELECTION: all applications are rev
 iewed\, qualified candidates advance to a technical test\, and finalists a
 re interviewed\, with decisions expected by early September. Applications 
 close 17 August 2026 (Anywhere on Earth)\; the programme starts 8 Septembe
 r 2026.\n\nOrganisation: AI Alignment Foundation\nLocation: Fully remote f
 or the 8-week research period\; hybrid Demo Day in Los Angeles with travel
  covered for those attending in person. Non-US applicants welcome if avail
 able for Pacific Time meetings.\nAward: USD 12\,000 stipend paid in two in
 stallments\, plus a compute budget. Travel covered for in-person Demo Day 
 attendance. No application fee.\nDuration: 8 weeks full-time at 40 hours p
 er week\, starting 8 September 2026\n\nMore: https://www.aialignmentfounda
 tion.org/fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://www.aialignmentfoundation.org/fellowship?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Fully remote for the 8-week research period\; hybrid Demo Day in L
 os Angeles with travel covered for those attending in person. Non-US appli
 cants welcome if available for Pacific Time meetings.
END:VEVENT
