UID:horizon-fellowship-2027-cohort@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115115Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260830
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260831
SUMMARY:Deadline: Horizon Fellowship\, 2027 Cohort
DESCRIPTION:The Horizon Fellowship places technologists\, scientists and re
 searchers with emerging-technology expertise into US federal agencies\, co
 ngressional offices and Washington DC think tanks to work on AI\, biotechn
 ology and emerging-technology policy. The 2027 cohort runs three tiers: ju
 nior fellows (under three years of experience\, no PhD) at a USD 78\,000 b
 ase for six months\; fellows (three or more years of relevant experience\,
  or a PhD) at USD 130\,000 for twelve months\; and a newly added senior fe
 llow tier (twelve or more years of experience with a leadership background
 ) at USD 190\,000 or more for twelve months. All tiers receive a USD 17\,0
 00 benefits stipend\, a USD 3\,000 professional development stipend and up
  to USD 3\,000 in relocation assistance\, and all are potentially renewabl
 e. The programme year begins with part-time remote training from January t
 o March 2027\, followed by matching in April and May and placement from sp
 ring or summer 2027 onward. Most offers are expected by the end of Novembe
 r 2026. ELIGIBILITY: no prior policy experience or specific degree is requ
 ired\, and Horizon explicitly welcomes candidates from diverse backgrounds
 \; fellows must reside in Washington DC for the placement\, and non-citize
 ns need work authorisation that does not depend on sponsorship. Applicatio
 ns close 30 August 2026 at 11:59pm Anywhere on Earth.\n\nOrganisation: Hor
 izon Institute for Public Service\nLocation: Washington DC\, USA (residenc
 e required for placement). Part-time remote training January to March 2027
 .\nAward: Base salary of USD 78\,000 for junior fellows\, USD 130\,000 for
  fellows\, and USD 190\,000 or more for senior fellows\, plus a USD 17\,00
 0 benefits stipend\, a USD 3\,000 professional development stipend\, and u
 p to USD 3\,000 relocation assistance. No application fee.\nDuration: 6 mo
 nths for junior fellows\, 12 months for fellows and senior fellows\, with 
 potential renewal. Part-time remote training January to March 2027\, match
 ing April to May 2027\, placement from summer 2027.\n\nMore: https://horiz
 onpublicservice.org/applications-open-for-2027-horizon-fellowship-cohort/?
 utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://horizonpublicservice.org/applications-open-for-2027-horizon-fel
 lowship-cohort/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, USA (residence required for placement). Part-time 
 remote training January to March 2027.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aaas-stpf-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115115Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261101
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261102
SUMMARY:Deadline: Science & Technology Policy Fellowships\, 2027-28 Class
DESCRIPTION:The AAAS Science & Technology Policy Fellowships place scientis
 ts and engineers inside US federal agencies\, congressional offices and th
 e judicial branch for a year of hands-on policymaking\, contributing techn
 ical knowledge and analytical skills to the federal policy process. AI\, d
 ata and computing policy placements are among the largest tracks\, and AAA
 S runs a dedicated AI legislative branch cohort that places AI experts in 
 congressional offices at GS-12 Step 10 on the DC locality scale. ELIGIBILI
 TY: US citizens holding a PhD or equivalent doctoral degree in any science
  or engineering field\, or a master's degree in engineering plus three yea
 rs of post-degree professional experience\; some tracks accept a bachelor'
 s plus five years. Relevant expertise includes AI\, machine learning\, com
 puter science\, robotics and data science. Fellows must reside in DC\, Mar
 yland or northern Virginia during the fellowship year. TIMELINE: the appli
 cation portal opens 1 August 2026 and closes 1 November 2026 at 11:59pm ET
 \, with eligibility notification in late November\, interview notification
  January to February 2027\, semi-finalist interviews in March\, placement 
 offers by early May\, and the fellowship year running 1 September 2027 to 
 31 August 2028. Apply through fellowshipapp.aaas.org.\n\nOrganisation: Ame
 rican Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS)\nLocation: Washing
 ton DC\, USA. Fellows are placed in US federal executive\, legislative and
  judicial branch offices and must reside in the DC area.\nAward: Stipend d
 epending on experience and placement\, roughly USD 85\,000 to 140\,000\; t
 he dedicated AI legislative branch cohort is paid at GS-12 Step 10 on the 
 DC locality scale. Includes health insurance\, a travel and professional d
 evelopment allowance\, and relocation support for some placements. No appl
 ication fee.\nDuration: One year\, 1 September 2027 to 31 August 2028\, re
 newable in some placements\n\nMore: https://www.aaas.org/programs/science-
 technology-policy-fellowships?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_me
 dium=referral
URL:https://www.aaas.org/programs/science-technology-policy-fellowships?utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, USA. Fellows are placed in US federal executive\, 
 legislative and judicial branch offices and must reside in the DC area.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wilson-center-research-fellowship-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115115Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260930
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261001
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wilson Center Research Fellowship\, 2027-2028 Class
DESCRIPTION:The Wilson Center\, the congressionally chartered nonpartisan p
 olicy research institution in Washington DC\, awards 10 to 20 research fel
 lowships for its 2027-2028 class. Fellows conduct research and write in th
 eir areas of interest while interacting with policymakers in Washington an
 d with other fellows. The Center accepts policy-relevant\, nonpartisan pro
 posals that address key foreign policy challenges confronting the United S
 tates and the world\, and projects must align with at least one of the Cen
 ter's four scholarship pillars: strategic competition\, economic statecraf
 t\, TECHNOLOGY AND INNOVATION\, and regional scholarship. The technology a
 nd innovation pillar is the relevant route for AI governance\, emerging te
 chnology and digital policy projects\, which the Center also supports thro
 ugh its Science and Technology Innovation Program. Fellows work remotely f
 or the duration of the fellowship\; the Center covers travel costs for two
  required trips to Washington DC at the beginning and the conclusion of th
 e term. The stipend is USD 10\,000 per month for the twelve-month term\, w
 hich runs 1 June 2027 to 30 May 2028. ELIGIBILITY: academic candidates nee
 d a PhD in hand and either a published book or monograph beyond the disser
 tation\, or a substantial body of research articles (five or more) in repu
 table peer-reviewed journals. Non-academic applicants (practitioners\, jou
 rnalists\, public intellectuals) need at least ten years of relevant exper
 ience and a record of substantial policy impact. There is no citizenship r
 estriction\, but English proficiency is required. Applications\, including
  letters of recommendation\, must be submitted online via Interfolio by 11
 :59pm ET on 30 September 2026. Questions: fellowships@wilsoncenter.org. NO
 TE: this is an open-topic foreign policy fellowship\, not an AI-specific o
 ne\; the technology angle depends on how you scope the proposal.\n\nOrgani
 sation: Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars\nLocation: Remote
  for the duration of the fellowship\, with two required trips to Washingto
 n DC (at the start and the end) for which travel costs are covered.\nAward
 : USD 10\,000 per month for a twelve-month fellowship\, plus covered trave
 l for the two required trips to Washington DC. No application fee.\nDurati
 on: Twelve months\, 1 June 2027 to 30 May 2028\n\nMore: https://www.wilson
 center.org/research-fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_m
 edium=referral
URL:https://www.wilsoncenter.org/research-fellowship?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote for the duration of the fellowship\, with two required trip
 s to Washington DC (at the start and the end) for which travel costs are c
 overed.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
